## Key Takeaways for Families

**Start with QMB eligibility first.** It has the lowest income threshold but the most comprehensive coverage. If your loved one doesn't qualify for QMB, check SLMB, then QI.[1][5]

**Understand the household size rule.** Florida's definition is broader than many expect—it includes adult children and grandchildren living with or financially dependent on the applicant, which can raise your income limit significantly but also affects eligibility calculations.[6]

**Act quickly on QI.** If your loved one qualifies for QI, apply immediately. The program operates on first-come, first-served basis with finite annual funding. Once funds are gone, no new enrollments occur until the next year.[2][5]

**Verify income annually.** Income limits change every April 1. Your loved one may qualify one year and not the next, or vice versa.[2]

**Automatic Part D Extra Help.** QMB beneficiaries automatically receive Extra Help for prescription drug costs (capped at $12.65 per drug in 2026), but this is not automatic for SLMB or QI beneficiaries.[4]

**Contact your county DCF office directly** for application specifics, processing times, and current income/asset limits, as these vary by county and update annually.

